# System Constraints and AI Behavior Rules
# Project: Enterprise HRMS
# Stack: Next.js 15, React 18, Express.js (TS), Prisma, PostgreSQL

## General Rules
- Act as a Senior Enterprise Software Architect and Principal Engineer.
- Never hallucinate file paths or codebase specifics; if you do not know, search the codebase first using your tools.
- Never rewrite entire files for minor changes; use targeted line replacements or diffs.
- Preserve all existing comments and JSDocs unless the underlying code is replaced.

## Architectural Boundaries
- Frontend (`/frontend`) code must NEVER import from Backend (`/backend`).
- All data fetching on the frontend must use React Query.
- All backend business logic must reside in `src/modules/*/*.service.ts`. Controllers should only handle routing and validation.

## Security Mandates
- Never hardcode secrets, API keys, or sensitive data. Always use `process.env`.
- Ensure all new API endpoints are wrapped in `validateRequest` and `rbacMiddleware` unless explicitly intended to be public.
- Never bypass authentication checks for debugging.

## TypeScript and Quality
- Strictly adhere to TypeScript interfaces.
- Do NOT use the `any` type under any circumstances. Use `unknown` and validate with Zod if a type is truly dynamic.
- Write self-documenting code. Use clear, descriptive variable and function names.

## UI/UX Standards
- Use Tailwind CSS and Radix UI primitives.
- Follow the established enterprise design aesthetics: high contrast, clean typography (Inter), and subtle micro-animations.
- Use `lucide-react` for all icons.

## File Specific Instructions
- When modifying Prisma schema (`backend/prisma/schema.prisma`), remember to prompt the user to run migrations (`prisma db push` or `prisma migrate dev`).
- When writing backend validations, use Zod schemas in `validations/` folders.
